Scene: Cersei taunts Ellaria and her daughter in the dungeon cell
Comparison:
There is no mention in the novels that Cersei insisted on breastfeeding Myrcella. Generally, she has always focused on Joffrey, and hardly paid any attention to Myrcella and Tommen.

Cersei says in the show "I never got to have a mother". In the books, Joanna Lannister died when Cersei was seven years old, thus she had enough time to get to know her mother.

Scene: Cersei does not care who sees Jaime in her bed
Comparison: In the books, Jaime and Cersei had sex for the last time after he returned to King's Landing, next to Joffrey's corpse. Ever since then, they have grown distant, and loathe each other.

Scene: The Iron Bank comes to collect its debts
Comparison:
In the books, it is not Tycho Nestoris but Noho Dimittis, another representative of the Iron Bank, who meets Cersei. The meeting takes place much earlier, and Cersei refuses to pay off the debt of the Iron Throne. Therefore, the Iron Bank decides to lend Stannis the funds he needs.

The Iron Bank never invested in slavery. Xaro and a custom officer named Qavo, not Tycho Nestoris, complain that Daenerys's disruption of the slave trade has had severe economic ripple effects across Essos. They do not tell that to Cersei.

Tycho Nestoris talks about dragons with Jon, not with Cersei. Cersei was partly responsible for Ned's death, but had nothing to do with the murders of Robb and Catelyn.

The Lannister army gives up Casterly Rock to attack Highgarden
Comparison:
In the books, Tywin never assigned Tyrion to build the sewers in Casterly Rock, only to clean them. The person to whom Tyrion tells about the sewers is not Daenerys but Kasporio, a member of the Second Sons.

Tyrion never made any tunnel inside Casterly Rock for sneaking whores. In order to meet Shae secretly, he used a secret tunnel leading from Chataya's brothel to a stable, and for the same purpose he used secret passages inside the Red Keep.

Scene: Jaime gives Olenna her death sentence
Comparison:
In the books, the lesson Jaime has learned from the Battle of the Whispering Wood is the opposite; he does not use Robb's strategy against enemies - instead, he takes precautions to make certain he will not be taken by surprise again.

There is no mention in the books that Jaime suffers from reading disorder. The gold mines of the Westerlands have not run dry in the books, they are as prosperous as ever.

Jaime was not present when Joffrey died at his wedding feast. He and Brienne arrived at King's Landing some time afterwards. Jaime has no idea who is Joffrey's murderer, and does not really care, because Joffrey meant nothing to him.

Tyrion, not Olenna, calls Jaime "poor fool", taunts him for being Cersei's minion, and claims (falsely) that he murdered Joffrey.
